\begin_layout Standard
SvK tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U\cup V)\simeq\pi_{1}(U)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap V)}\pi_{1}(V)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So presumably 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}(U\cup V\cup W)=\pi_{1}((U\cup V)\cup W)\simeq\pi_{1}(U\cup V)*_{\pi_{1}((U\cup V)\cap W)}\pi_{1}(W)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\simeq\pi_{1}(U)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap V)}\pi_{1}(V)*_{\pi_{1}((U\cup V)\cap W)}\pi_{1}(W)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\simeq\pi_{1}(U)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap V)}\pi_{1}(V)*_{\pi_{1}((U\cap W)\cup(V\cap W))}\pi_{1}(W)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But then we have to unpack what it means to amalgamate over 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}((U\cap W)\cup(V\cap W))$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}((U\cap W)\cup(V\cap W))\simeq\pi_{1}(U\cap W)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap V\cap W)}\pi_{1}(V\cap W)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And substitute that back to get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}(U)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap V)}\pi_{1}(V)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap W)*_{\pi_{1}(U\cap V\cap W)}\pi_{1}(V\cap W)}\pi_{1}(W)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is unreadable, but hopefully correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It doesn't seem like the order of which amalgamated free products are nested
 within each other should matter, though: what matters is that we have all
 the relations in the diagram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have the presentations 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)=\left\langle S_{U}|R_{U}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(V)=\left\langle S_{V}|R_{V}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(W)=\left\langle S_{W}|R_{W}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{uvw}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap V\cap W)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}(h_{uvw})=i_{2}(h_{uvw})=i_{3}(h_{uvw})$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{uv}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1}(h_{uv})=j_{2}(h_{uv})$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{wv}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{3}(h_{wv})=j_{4}(h_{wv})$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{uw}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{5}(h_{uw})=j_{6}(h_{uw})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Putting that all together, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}(U\cup V\cup W)\simeq\langle S_{U},S_{V},S_{W}|R_{U},R_{W},R_{W},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall h_{uvw}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap V\cap W)\ i_{1}(h_{uvw})=i_{2}(h_{uvw})=i_{3}(h_{uvw}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ \forall h_{uv}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap V)\ j_{1}(h_{uv})=j_{2}(h_{uv})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ \forall h_{wv}\in\pi_{1}(V\cap W)\ j_{3}(h_{wv})=j_{4}(h_{wv})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ \forall h_{uw}\in\pi_{1}(U\cap W)j_{5}(h_{uw})=j_{6}(h_{uw})\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gemini 2.5 Pro claims that we don't actually need the triple-intersection
 relations because they're implied by the pairwise relations by transitivity,
 so this is actually simpler than the alternating sums of the inclusion–exclusio
n principle.
\end_layout

