\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example 1
\series default
.
 What about three annuluses, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

? We can see that the union should just be a thicker annulus (or our proposed
 generalization should compute the same result formally).
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)\simeq\mathbb{Z}\simeq\left\langle u|\varnothing\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(V)\simeq\mathbb{Z}\simeq\left\langle v|\varnothing\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(W)\simeq\mathbb{Z}\simeq\left\langle w|\varnothing\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

 are also annuluses.
 A loop in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 has to get mapped to the same element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(V)$
\end_inset

, and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, so we end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u,v,w|u=v,v=w\right\rangle \simeq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example 2
\series default
.
 Let's try gluing three punctured toruses together.
 We know that a punctured torus is homotopy equivalent to a figure eight,
 because the corners are identified as a point, and then the top and bottom
 and left and right edges become the loops: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)\simeq\mathbb{Z}*\mathbb{Z}\simeq\left\langle a,b|\varnothing\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(V)\simeq\mathbb{Z}*\mathbb{Z}\simeq\left\langle c,d|\varnothing\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(W)\simeq\mathbb{Z}*\mathbb{Z}\simeq\left\langle e,f|\varnothing\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three of the pairwise intersections are annuluses: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U\cap V)\simeq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U\cap W)\simeq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(V\cap W)\simeq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's think about the inclusion homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1}:\pi_{1}(U\cap V)\to\pi_{1}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{2}:\pi_{1}(U\cap V)\to\pi_{1}(V)$
\end_inset

, for which we must add relations.
 A loop in 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a boundary loop in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and those boundary loops have to be identified.
 A boundary loop on the punctured torus is 
\begin_inset Formula $aba^{-1}b^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So our group ends up being 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a,b,c,d,e,f|aba^{-1}b^{-1}=cdc^{-1}d^{-1}=efe^{-1}f^{-1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

?
